STEP 1: Understand the Dataset
Your Excel file has 7 key sheets (tables), typically:

Sales_Data â€“ Fact table (contains Sales Amount, Quantity, Order Date, ProductKey, etc.)
SalesOrder_Data â€“ Order-level details (Order ID, CustomerKey, etc.)
Customer_Data â€“ Customer demographics (name, gender, age, income, etc.)
Product_Data â€“ Product details (category, subcategory, price, cost, etc.)
Reseller_Data â€“ Reseller information (for B2B sales)
SalesTerritory_Data â€“ Region, Country, and Territory info
Date_Data â€“ Calendar table (date, month, quarter, year)

ğŸŸ© Goal: Build a star schema â†’ Sales_Data is the central fact table, all others are dimension tables.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In Customer_Data and Reseller_Data, the first row often has:

| CustomerKey | CustomerName | ... |
|--------------|---------------|
| -1 | Not Applicable | ... |

ğŸ’¡ Meaning:
-1 is a placeholder (dummy key) used when a sale record in the fact table (Sales_Data) doesnâ€™t have a matching customer or reseller.
Instead of leaving it blank or NULL, data engineers use -1 to maintain referential integrity between fact and dimension tables.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2: Data Cleaning
In Power Query (Transform Data):
âœ… Remove duplicates (especially in Customer or Product tables)
âœ… Ensure correct data types:
Date columns â†’ Date
Price, Sales, Profit â†’ Decimal Number
Keys â†’ Whole Number
âœ… Rename columns clearly (e.g., Product_Name, Customer_ID)
âœ… Handle nulls â€” replace with â€œUnknownâ€ or 0 as needed
âœ… Ensure consistent date formats (e.g., M/d/yyyy)
âœ… Format currencies â†’ USD (or your local currency)

STEP 3: Data Modeling (Relationships)
In Model view:

Relationship	Type
Sales_Data[CustomerKey] â†’ Customer_Data[CustomerKey]	Many-to-One
Sales_Data[ProductKey] â†’ Product_Data[ProductKey]	Many-to-One
Sales_Data[ResellerKey] â†’ Reseller_Data[ResellerKey]	Many-to-One
Sales_Data[SalesTerritoryKey] â†’ SalesTerritory_Data[SalesTerritoryKey]	Many-to-One
Sales_Data[OrderDateKey] â†’ Date_Data[DateKey]	Many-to-One

â¡ï¸ Star Schema: One fact table (Sales) surrounded by lookup tables.

STEP 4: DAX Measures
Here are key DAX formulas to create:
Measure	Formula
| Measure                  | Formula                                                             |
| ------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Total Sales**          | `SUM(Sales_Data[SalesAmount])`                                      |
| **Total Orders**         | `DISTINCTCOUNT(Sales_Data[SalesOrderNumber])`                       |
| **Total Quantity**       | `SUM(Sales_Data[OrderQuantity])`                                    |
| **Total Profit**         | `SUMX(Sales_Data, Sales_Data[SalesAmount] - Sales_Data[TotalCost])` |
| **Profit Margin %**      | `DIVIDE([Total Profit], [Total Sales])`                             |
| **Average Order Value**  | `DIVIDE([Total Sales], [Total Orders])`                             |
| **Sales LY (Last Year)** | `CALCULATE([Total Sales], SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(Date_Data[FullDate]))` |
| **YoY Growth %**         | `DIVIDE([Total Sales] - [Sales LY], [Sales LY])`                    |

